		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/12/20/business/Wolf/Wolf-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/12/20/business/Wolf/Wolf-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/12/20/business/Wolf/Wolf-blog480.jpg" id="100000002612765" width="480" height="320" alt="Leonardo DiCaprio in the film âThe Wolf of Wall Street.â"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Leonardo DiCaprio in the film âThe Wolf of Wall Street.â</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Mary Cybulski/Paramount Pictures</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div class="inlineModule"><div class="entry"><h6 class="kicker"><a href="//boss.blogs.nytimes.com/category/the-next-level/">The Next Level</a></h6><p class="summary">Avoiding the pitfalls of fast growth.</p></div></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I went to see &#8220;The Wolf of Wall Street,&#8221; and I think Martin Scorsese, the famed director, just nailed how business cultures are created in fast-growth companies. He took it over the top with the Hollywood glamour, vulgarity and corruption, but he got a lot of it right â I just wish he could have left out the corruption.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He portrayed a culture none of us would want to emulate but it was right there in living color so you have to give him credit for highlighting real-world lessons. Two of them were: You can&#8217;t build a culture in a comfort zone and there is a dark side in the drive to be first.Â Both of these points are true but are often overlooked in academic and consulting circles.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I am convinced that Mr. Scorsese noticed that little has been done well on the topic of corporate culture so he made it the whole point of this movie instead of just doing his usual one man&#8217;s crime career. Most of all, he showed how you can take ordinary people and make them maniacs for the mission. Remove the corruption and some unnecessary vileness, and we can learn a lot about fast growth from this movie. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-81555"></span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">First, if the mission is only about money, it wonât last. But as the movie showed â and as I have observed in real life â boy does it have its moments. But embarking on a money-driven mission is not the way to build companies that last. As I sat watched the movie with all of its laughter, bluster and lust, I knew things were not going to turn out well.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Quite frankly, I had pretty much the same queasy feeling that I get when I sit in front of entrepreneurs who say they are going to consolidate and merge companies to save money and capture economies of scale. The classic example is the doctor group companies that consolidated in the &#8217;90s to save money. Most blew up before they reached 70 people. Mr. Scorsese, it seemed to me, was putting out a big yellow flag for entrepreneurs: Don&#8217;t do it just for the money!</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But that is not his only home run on the dangers of fast growth. I have never seen anyone else capture so thoroughly the sheer frenzy that exists in a fast-growth company on a market tear. Everyone in the movie is moving with a purpose for the chief executive, Leonardo DiCaprioâs Jordan Belfort. But this is not a runaway train to nowhere. This is a fast-moving train to everywhere. Itâs not picture-perfect going down the track, but it gets the job done, and it gets it done fast.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Scorseseâs next home run is picking up on the need for a rallying cry. I am not talking about the usual human resources Pollyannas who say things like âlisten to your customers.â The companiesÂ I&#8217;m talking about are already doing that or they would not be experiencing fast growth. Mr. Belfort&#8217;s rallying cry of &#8220;Don&#8217;t take no for an answer&#8221; is specific to the mission of the company. In short, it is not fluff. It is real. At the information technology company I founded, we used the rallying cry &#8220;total contact ownership,&#8221; which meant that all employees owned the resolution to any problems that hit their radar â no passing or transferring, period.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">If I ever veered off and violated the rallying cry, I was challenged instantly, usually by my No. 2. And thatâs another fast-growth lesson in the movie: the importance of a No. 2, played here by Jonah Hill. Mr. Belfort&#8217;s No. 2 would not challenge the C.E.O. for his job but would push back when Mr. Belfort was going to violate his own code â by taking no for an answer from the Securities and Exchange Commission. O.K., maybe this wasnât the purest of causes, but we donât hear enough about this kind of culture.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Scorsese also demonstrates why fast growth is so hard, so rare and almost impossible to teach. He shows that not only do you need people who are entirely dedicated to the company&#8217;s success but you also need huge egos in individual roles within the company. Yes, teamwork is good but it is way overrated.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Scorsese showed the raw, energetic egos an entrepreneur like Mr. Belfort needed to go from a no-name company in a remote warehouse selling pink-sheet stocks to a giant on Wall Street selling initial public offerings. Everybody had the desire not only to be No. 1 but to be 10 times better than the competition. This is why I would choose 10 ego-driven people over 10 team players any day of the week.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I can&#8217;t teach someone to accept that they are inadequate unless they are No. 1, but I can teach 10 ego-driven people to be good team players: Don&#8217;t hog the ball, earn everything you get and treat your teammates the way you would want to be treated. In short, you can be an ego-driven wolf but not a raging bull.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><i>Cliff Oxford is the founder of the </i><a title="The company's Web site." href="//www.oxford-center.com/"><i>Oxford Center for Entrepreneurs</i></a><i>. You can </i><a title="The Oxford Center's Twitter feed." href="https://www.twitter.com/OxfordCent"><i>follow him on Twitter</i></a><i>.</i></p>
	</div>
